In Connecticut schools spending is up, but students are still struggling

Sasha Allen | allensasha622@gmail.com | 443-386-7386
June 7, 2025


In 2022, one in three students were at risk of dropping of dropping out, and chronic absenteeism continues to be an issue. Despite this, Connecticut has increased spending on education over the past decade.

So, whats going on in Connecticut schools?

The state is undergoing what they call the Disconnected Youth Crisis. Students are struggling in multiple aspects of school, and these struggles have long-term consequences. As a result, young people are not entering the job market or pursuing higher education after either dropping out or graduating.

The state created a method of looking at the overall performance of their schools called the Next Generation Accountability System which is based off of 12 broad factor indicators of student performance:

  • Academic achievement status measured by state assessments
  • Academic growth
  • Assessment participation rate
  • Chronic absenteeism
  • Postsecondary preparation - coursework
  • Postsecondary readiness exams and college credit
  • Graduation on track in ninth grade
  • Graduation four-year adjusted cohort graduation rate all students
  • Graduation six-year adjusted cohort graduation rate high needs
  • Postsecondary entrance rate all students (college enrollment)
  • Physical fitness
  • Arts access

Each school has a point maximum based on the opportunities and level of school, and is given a score and an accountability index, or the percent of the total maximum points earned, to gauge what level a school or district is at.

Funding levels continue to rise as student test scores fall.

Connecticut has increased spending on education over the past decade. Despite this, students in the state are not performing well. In 2022, one in three students were at risk of not graduating high school according to a report released in October of 2023.

How does this compare nationally?

Connecticut spends more on education than most states across the nation. But how much exactly are they spending, and what is the national average for per-pupil spending on education?

State actions

This story is extremely timely because this issue has been brought to light in the past two years. A report was published in October of 2023 detailing the failures of the state, and this report has sparked the introduction of legislation into the Connecticut Senate. The legislation proposed an increase in funding for at-risk students and better data collection methods and data collaboration, but was not passed by the end of session.

The target audience for this story is anyone in Connecticut who is in the school system or knows anyone involved in the school system including parents, teachers, students, family members and friends of students. This way, they can be more informed on what the state is trying to do as well as the contributing factors to the crisis.

Highly affected districts

Bridegport, Waterbury, Hartford and New Haven have some of the highest rates of poverty in the state. They were also among the ten districts with more than 1,000 students performing at the lowest levels in the state.

People to interview

  • Rep.Anthony L. Nolan, introduced a bill to increase education funding.
  • Donna Hamzy, helped craft the Young Peoples Plan, which is a ten year plan for funding to help the crisis.
  • State Department of Education Commissioner Charlene Russell-Tucker
  • Someone who testified during the legislative hearings could be a good place to start finding people closely connected to the issue, preferably a student who has experienced disconnection in the school system. (https://www.cga.ct.gov/aspx/CGADisplayTestimonies/CGADisplayTestimony.aspx?bill=SB-01511&doc_year=2025)

Going forward

I would like to compare the median household income or the poverty rates in each district to the accountability index. I could also take a more micro look at test scores and the factors going into the accountability index.

This could possibly impact the funding for education, although it seems like there is already some initiative to change policy. Hopefully from this more nonprofits will be able to help supplement in high need areas from this as well.

I was mainly interested in this story because I had never heard of the disconnected youth crisis before and for a rich state known for having a fairly good education system, and wondered why so many students were at risk of dropping out.

Estimated delivery is beginning of July.
